His most cele· brated painting was that of Aphrodite rising froin the sea, which existed in the time of Augustus, and was placed by him in the temple of Julius Caesar.

Lysippus was a younger contemporary of Apelles, and anat-ive of Sicyon. He wrought almost entirely in bronze, and was the author of the statue from which the Farnese Hercules was copied by Glycon. · He made several statues of Alexander, whom he ap· pears like Apelles to have followed into Asia.
